select() plus filter()
penguins |&gt; 
  select(species, sex, year, island) |&gt; 
  filter(island == "Torgersen")

arrange() changes order of observations
penguins |&gt; arrange(desc(bill_length_mm))

penguins |&gt;
  select(species, contains("bill")) |&gt;
  filter(!species == "Adelie") |&gt;
  arrange(desc(bill_length_mm)) 

penguins |&gt;
  select(species, contains("bill")) |&gt;
  filter(!species == "Adelie") |&gt; 
  arrange(desc(species), bill_length_mm)

group_by() aggregates data for next function
# group by alone? not that useful
penguins |&gt; 
  group_by(island, sex)

# group by and count
penguins |&gt; 
  group_by(island, sex) |&gt; 
  count()

# group by and calculate mean body mass
penguins |&gt; 
  group_by(island, sex) |&gt;
  summarize(body_mass_mean = mean(body_mass_g, na.rm = TRUE))

count() counts tot obs. by group
# total penguins by sex without count
penguins |&gt; 
  group_by(sex) |&gt; 
  summarize(total = n())

# with count
penguins |&gt;
  count(sex)

Method 3: Reorder the bars using tidyverse fct_infreq()
fct_infreq() sorts bars automatically by how common each category is (most to least frequent)
scorecard |&gt;
  mutate(type = fct_infreq(type)) |&gt;
ggplot(aes(x = type)) +
  geom_bar()

Definition of For Loops
‚ÄúFor loops‚Äù are the most common looping construct in many programming languages. They are used to iterate over the elements of an object (usually a list or vector) and perform an action on each one.
Syntax:
for (item in sequence of items) {
  action to be repeated for each item   
}
Example:
for (item in c(1,2,3)) {
  print(item)
}

Nested For Loops
For loops can be nested, so the outer loop controls how many times the entire inner loop runs from start to finish:

for (i in c(1,2,3)) {
  print(i)
  for (j in c("cat", "dog", "squirrel", "rabbit")) {
    print(j)
  }
}

Let‚Äôs break this code down:

The outer loop runs 3 times
For each execution of the outer loop, the inner loop runs 4 times
That‚Äôs a total of 3 √ó 4 = 12 inner loop outputs, plus 3 outer loop prints

Importing CSV files
To load data into R we need importing functions. There are several of them depending on the type of file we want to import. See ‚ÄúR for Data Science‚Äù 2nd Ed. Chapter 7 for details.
The most common importing functions read comma-separated values (csv) files. Two main versions:

from base-R we have read.csv()
from readr we have read_csv()

They are similar, but we use read_csv() in this course because is more recent, faster, and does not automatically changes data types (e.g., does not convert characters into factors automatically). Type ?read.csv() and ?read_csv() in your Console for info.

Same code rewritten with Tidyverse Syntax

twitter |&gt;
  mutate(
    tot_likes_retweets = likes + retweets,
    high_engagement    = tot_likes_retweets &gt;= 80
  ) |&gt;
  filter(language == "en" & high_engagement == TRUE) |&gt;
  inner_join(state_lookup, by = "state") |&gt;
  summarise(avg_total = mean(tot_likes_retweets, na.rm = TRUE))

Rewriting the Same Code with the Tidyverse
tw_full &lt;- twitter |&gt;
  mutate(
    tot_likes_retweets = likes + retweets,
    high_engagement = tot_likes_retweets &gt;= 80) |&gt;
  filter(language == "en" & high_engagement == TRUE) |&gt;
  inner_join(state_lookup, by = "state")

sum_inter &lt;- tw_full |&gt;
  summarise(sum_inter = sum(tot_likes_retweets))

sum_inter_by_vote &lt;- tw_full |&gt;
  group_by(vote) |&gt;
  summarise(sum_inter_by_vote = sum(tot_likes_retweets))
